article.headline: Iverson misses second game with finger injury
article.story:
TORONTO (AP) -- Donyell Marshall felt relieved after Toronto ended its losing streak and extended Philadelphia's. Marshall had 19 points and 10 rebounds as the Raptors snapped a five-game losing skid with a 94-84 victory over the shorthanded 76ers on Wednesday night. "We just wanted to go out there and make a statement," said Marshall, who scored 10 of Toronto's first 11 points. "We wanted to get our losing streak over." Allen Iverson, the NBA's leading scorer, missed his second straight game because of sprained right index finger. Philadelphia has lost four straight and six of seven, falling to 19-27. Morris Peterson added 18 points and Vince Carter 17 for the Raptors, who had five players in double figures. Toronto's Jalen Rose had 13 assists and nine points. "We were tired of losing," Carter said. "It's been a tough five-game stretch but there are other teams that have lost five or more games. We figure we are too good to let a ridiculous streak go on." Philadelphia's Glenn Robinson went 4-for-14 from the field for 16 points in 36 minutes. Robinson complained about playing time after Tuesday night's blowout loss to New Jersey. Philadelphia coach Randy Ayers addressed Robinson's complaints during a team meeting early Wednesday. Ayers also talked about Eric Snow's and Aaron McKie's recent comments about the team's lack of identity. "Some of the coaches spoke out, and spoke from their heart. If that's not enough to motivate you, what will?" McKie said. Robinson said the meeting smoothed things over. "We got things straightened out, we all have the same objectives, to come out and win," Robinson said. Kenny Thomas cut Toronto's lead to four early in the fourth quarter, but Carter made two straight jumpers and Peterson capped a 10-1 run with a 3-pointer, giving Toronto a 13-point lead with 4:26 left. Marshall's 3-pointer gave Toronto an 11-point lead with 3:13 left, and Bosh's layup made it 92-82 with 54 seconds remaining. "I was really pleased with our effort," Ayers said. "We came out and really got after some people and played the way we're capable of playing. I can't fault our effort." Carter looked tentative in his third game back after missing three with a quadriceps injury. He is 16-for-51 from the field over the three games. Peterson had 13 points for the Raptors, who led by as many as 13 in the first half.

Game notes
Robinson played 18 minutes in Tuesday's loss. "By no means was he being punished," Ayers said. "He's played extremely well for us the last three or four weeks. If you notice, I don't think any of our starters played a quarter in the second half." ... Toronto forward Jerome Moiso played for the first time since Dec. 9. ... The Raptors shot 50 percent, just the second time this season they've shot 50 percent or better.
